portal. — Product Requirements Document (v1)

**Last updated:** February 2026

---

## Product in one sentence

portal. helps you find something worth doing, plan it, and share what you know — through people you trust, not algorithms.

---

## Core persona

**The Intentional Explorer** — 25–38, urban, culturally active. Has strong taste in food, music, art, and nightlife. Travels regularly and has friends scattered across cities. Frustrated by generic recommendations on Google Maps, Yelp, and TripAdvisor. Trusts specific people over aggregate scores.

Currently pieces plans together from Instagram stories, group chats, Google Maps saves, and screenshots. Most of the time, defaults to what they already know because the friction of finding something new is too high.

**Primary job-to-be-done:** Go from "I have free time" to "I know exactly what I'm doing" in under two minutes.

---

## Three core flows

Everything in v1 exists to serve one of these three flows. If a feature doesn't directly support one, it's not in the app.

---

### Flow 1: Find something worth doing

**Trigger:** Weekend approaching, evening free, visiting a city, friend asks "what should we do?"

**Outcome:** User goes from "no idea" to "I have a shortlist of good options" — or all the way to a shareable plan.

**Steps:**

**1. Express intent.**
User opens the app. At the top of the discover feed, two rows of filter pills allow the user to express what they're looking for:

- **Row 1 — Time:** `Tonight` · `Tomorrow` · `This Weekend` · `Sat` · `Sun` · `Pick a date`. Single-select — tapping one deselects the previous. Tapping the active pill again deselects it (returns to browse mode).
- **Row 2 — Category:** `Food` · `Drinks` · `Music` · `Art` · `Markets` · `Community`. Multi-select — the user can combine categories (e.g., Food + Drinks). Tapping an active category deselects it.

Every tap immediately reshapes the feed. There is no "apply" button — the content updates in real time as filters change.

When no time filter is active, the feed is in **browse mode**: all content is visible, editorially mixed, optimized for casual exploration. When a time filter is selected, the feed enters **planning mode**: time-relevant events and spots surface to the top, and evergreen content (permanent spots, general collections) is deprioritized below.

The time filter is the mode switch. There is no explicit toggle or tab — the user's expression of time intent reshapes the entire surface.

**2. Browse.**
The feed is a single scrollable surface with events and spots interleaved. There are no tabs separating content types — the user cares about "is this worth doing?", not whether it's technically a spot or an event.

Each card shows:
- Hero image filling the card frame
- Name
- Category
- Neighborhood
- Trust signal: who created or saved it (avatar + handle), save count
- Events additionally show: date and time

Cards are ordered by a combination of editorial quality, recency, and trust relevance (friend saves weighted higher than stranger saves). The feed also includes discovery sections interspersed with cards — see the Discover surface description below for full section breakdown.

**3. Evaluate.**
Tapping a card opens a detail screen. The top fold — visible without scrolling — answers four questions:

- *What is it?* — Name + category + tags
- *When?* — Date/time (events) or "Open" (spots)
- *Where?* — Neighborhood + distance from user
- *Why trust this?* — Who created it, who saved it, total save count

Below the fold: full description, ticket link (if event), map showing location, and the hosts/owners attributed to the item.

The primary action on this screen is **Save** — prominently placed, one tap.

**4. Save.**
One tap. No "which collection?" prompt. No confirmation dialog. The item goes to the user's unsorted personal saves list. This is the moment value is delivered for most users most of the time — they save 3–5 things over the course of browsing and go do 1–2 of them without ever formally organizing.

The save action is available on every card surface: in the feed, in the map card preview, and on the detail screen. It behaves identically everywhere.

**5. Organize (optional).**
If the user wants to go beyond a loose shortlist, they can create a named collection and pull saved items into it. This step is never prompted or pushed — the user initiates it themselves from the Profile tab. See the Collections section below for full detail.

For the majority of use cases — "I saved 3 things for Saturday, I'll pick one" — the unsorted saves list is the plan. Formal organization is for higher-stakes situations: multi-day trips, coordinating with friends, building a recommendation list for others.

---

### Flow 2: Share what you know

**Trigger:** Friend is visiting my city. Someone asks "where should I eat in Barcelona?" User found something great and wants to share it more durably than an Instagram story that disappears in 24 hours.

**Outcome:** A curated, named, shareable collection that works as a self-contained artifact — useful whether the recipient has the app or not.

**Steps:**

**1. Save things over time.**
Identical to flow 1, step 4. The user has been saving spots and events for themselves through normal use of the app. Their accumulated saves represent their taste.

**2. Organize into a collection.**
The user creates a new collection from the Profile tab and names it with the audience in mind: "Barcelona Essentials", "Best Natural Wine Bars in Poblenou", "This Weekend's Picks." They then add items from their saves into this collection. See the Collections section for the full mechanics.

**3. Set visibility.**
Every collection has a visibility setting with three options:
- **Private** (default) — only the creator sees it
- **Friends** — visible to approved followers
- **Public** — visible to everyone, appears on the user's profile, discoverable in the feed and through search

Changing visibility is a single tap on the collection. The moment a collection is set to Public, it becomes part of the app's discovery ecosystem — other users can find it, save it, and follow the creator based on it.

**4. Share.**
Tapping share on any collection generates a link. The user sends this link through any messaging app (WhatsApp, iMessage, etc.). The link opens a read-only web view of the collection showing all items with their details — no account required to view it. If the recipient has the app, tapping an item opens it natively.

Public collections additionally live on the creator's profile permanently, where anyone who visits the profile can browse them.

**How flow 2 connects to flow 1:** Public collections from other users appear in the discover feed. When a user's public collections accumulate saves from others, that user becomes someone worth following. The path from casual user to influential curator is organic — it happens through the quality of their collections, not through any explicit status or verification.

---

### Flow 3: Put your thing on the map

**Trigger:** Venue has a show Friday, restaurant just opened, promoter booked a lineup, pop-up market happening this weekend.

**Outcome:** The event or spot is live in the app — visible on the map, in the discover feed for users filtering by matching time/area/category, and in the feeds of the creator's followers.

**Steps:**

**1. Create.**
From the Profile tab, the user taps "+" next to My Events or My Spots. A single creation form adapts to the content type:

**For events (things with a date):**
- Required: name, category, location, date, time, one image, short description
- Optional: end time, price, ticket link, tags, additional hosts

**For spots (permanent places):**
- Required: name, category, location, one image, short description
- Optional: price range, tags, additional owners

The form is short and focused — it asks only for what a potential visitor needs to decide whether to go. There is no rich text editor, no multi-image gallery, no complex scheduling.

Secondary creation entry point: long-pressing on the map creates a new event or spot with the location pre-filled.

**2. Publish.**
The item goes live immediately upon submission. It appears:
- As a pin on the map
- In the discover feed for users whose active filters (time, category, location) match
- In the feeds of anyone following the creator

There is no review queue, no approval process. Content is live instantly.

**3. See traction.**
The creator sees the save count on their item — visible on the item's detail screen and on the card wherever it appears. "34 people saved your event" is the signal that the right audience found it. There are no other analytics in v1.

